<DocsLayout title="ctx_benchmark — Real Project Benchmarks" description="Benchmark compression strategies with real token measurements, latency tracking, and AST-based preservation scoring.">
  <p>
    <code>ctx_benchmark</code> measures real token counts using tiktoken (o200k_base — the same tokenizer
    used by GPT-4 and Claude). It supports two modes: <strong>single-file</strong> benchmarks and
    <strong>project-wide</strong> scans.
  </p>

  <h2>Project Benchmark (v2.1.0)</h2>
  <p>
    Scans your project directory, selects up to 50 representative files across all languages,
    and measures every compression mode with real data.
  </p>

  <h3>CLI Usage</h3>
  <pre><code># Terminal output (ANSI)
lean-ctx benchmark run [path]

# Machine-readable JSON
lean-ctx benchmark run [path] --json

# Shareable Markdown report
lean-ctx benchmark report [path]</code></pre>

  <h3>MCP Usage</h3>
  <pre><code>ctx_benchmark path="." action="project" format="terminal"
ctx_benchmark path="." action="project" format="markdown"
ctx_benchmark path="." action="project" format="json"</code></pre>

  <h3>What It Measures</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Metric</th><th>How</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><strong>Token count per mode</strong></td><td>tiktoken o200k_base on actual compressed output</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Savings %</strong></td><td><code>1 - compressed_tokens / raw_tokens</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Latency</strong></td><td>Wall-clock time per compression operation (<code>std::time::Instant</code>)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><strong>Preservation quality</strong></td><td>AST-based: what % of functions, exports, imports survive compression</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Example Output</h3>
  <pre><code>══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  lean-ctx Benchmark — .
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
  Scanned: 50 files (10 ts, 10 rs, 8 py, 6 go, ...)
  Total raw tokens: 145.2K

  Mode Performance:
  Mode               Tokens    Savings    Latency    Quality
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  map                  7.5K      98.5%      2.3ms      93.4%
  signatures           9.3K      98.2%      2.1ms      96.3%
  aggressive         130.1K      10.4%       81μs     100.0%
  entropy            108.3K      25.4%     26.0ms     100.0%
  cache_hit             650      99.6%        0μs        N/A

  Session Simulation (30-min coding):
  Approach                     Tokens       Cost    Savings
  ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
  Raw (no compression)         290.4K     $0.726          —
  lean-ctx (no CCP)             38.2K     $0.096      86.8%
  lean-ctx + CCP                12.4K     $0.031      95.7%
══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════</code></pre>

  <h3>Session Simulation</h3>
  <p>
    The benchmark simulates a realistic 30-minute coding session using your project's actual files:
  </p>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>15 file reads</strong> — mix of full and map modes, using real token counts from your files</li>
    <li><strong>10 cache hits</strong> — re-reads at 13 tokens each</li>
    <li><strong>8 shell commands</strong> — estimated at typical compression ratios</li>
    <li><strong>Session resume</strong> — compares full re-read vs. CCP state (~400 tokens)</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Preservation Scoring</h3>
  <p>
    Quality scores are computed using tree-sitter AST parsing. For each compressed output, lean-ctx checks
    how many <strong>functions</strong>, <strong>exports</strong>, and <strong>imports</strong> from the
    original file are still present. A score of 93.4% means 93.4% of all code symbols survived compression.
  </p>

  <h2>Single-File Benchmark</h2>
  <p>
    Benchmarks a single file against all compression strategies with exact token counts.
  </p>

  <h3>Parameters</h3>
  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr><th>Parameter</th><th>Type</th><th>Required</th><th>Description</th></tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr><td><code>path</code></td><td>string</td><td>Yes</td><td>File path (single file) or directory (project mode)</td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>action</code></td><td>string</td><td>No</td><td><code>file</code> (default) or <code>project</code></td></tr>
      <tr><td><code>format</code></td><td>string</td><td>No</td><td><code>terminal</code> (default), <code>markdown</code>, or <code>json</code> (project mode only)</td></tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <h3>Example (Single File)</h3>
  <pre><code>ctx_benchmark auth.ts

Benchmark: auth.ts (123L)

Strategy                     Tokens   Savings
──────────────────────────────────────────────
raw                             915  —
aggressive                      412  -503 (55%)
signatures (compact)            121  -794 (87%)
signatures (tdd)                 98  -817 (89%)
entropy                         348  -567 (62%)
cache hit                        13  -902 (99%)
──────────────────────────────────────────────
Best: "cache hit" saves 902 tokens (99%)</code></pre>

  <h2>When to Use</h2>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Project benchmark</strong>: Run on your project to get real, shareable numbers for your specific codebase. Share the Markdown report on GitHub or LinkedIn.</li>
    <li><strong>Single-file benchmark</strong>: Run on specific files to decide which <code>ctx_read</code> mode works best for that file type.</li>
  </ul>
</DocsLayout>
